summary: Actively opposed proposed cuts to Medicaid and SNAP that would affect veterans and vulnerable households; offered rejected amendments in House Veterans' Affairs Committee markup to preserve veterans' access to health care and nutrition assistance (including making veterans who lose Medicaid between Jan 20, 2025 and Jan 19, 2029 eligible for VA Priority Group 6, and requiring the VA Secretary to provide a cash subsidy for nutrition assistance directly to veterans). Criticized majority committee actions that he says prioritize tax breaks for the wealthy over essential supports for veterans and low-income families. At a February 2025 town hall, he reiterated his strong opposition to cuts to Medicaid and SNAP, framed those cuts as being advanced to pay for "an enormous tax break to the wealthiest," and urged constituents to organize and advocate against such proposals.

Gill argues that Somali immigrants have high rates of reliance on public benefits and uses those claims to justify immigration restrictions. In his Somalia moratorium proposal he cited statistics he attributed to Somali households (e.g., high percentages on welfare, Medicaid, and food stamps) and framed the moratorium as necessary to protect taxpayers, fiscal responsibility, and facilitate integration of those already in the U.S. In January 2026 he highlighted a Minnesota Somali fraud scandal in a House Oversight hearing, alleging Somali organizations committed fraud in welfare and other programs and funneled American funds overseas, and called for DOJ investigations and accountability. In June 2025 he supported measures (through the New IDEA Act and related rhetoric) to use SSA and IRS data-sharing to identify unauthorized workers and to block what he describes as illegal aliens from abusing Social Security and other benefits meant for Americans, framing enforcement as protecting taxpayers and program integrity. He also opposed demands he says would provide 'taxpayer funded handouts for illegal aliens' amid a fiscal-appropriations lapse, calling such funding a nonstarter for his district. In November 2025 he publicly characterized Democratic shutdown demands as seeking 'handouts for illegal aliens,' using the shutdown dispute to reiterate his opposition to federal benefit expansions for unauthorized immigrants.

Advocates for policies to reduce poverty and strengthen social supports; has cosponsored measures to enhance SNAP access, expand housing affordability and homelessness prevention (Housing is a Human Right Act, Ending Homelessness Act), and other anti-poverty initiatives to support low-income families. Recently celebrated a $622,637 federal grant awarded to the Tohono Oâ€™odham Kiki Housing Authority to provide rental assistance to roughly 20 Native American veterans, highlighting the need to address historic disinvestment in tribal communities and to secure sustained federal resources for tribal housing and veteran supports. Has also criticized large DHS/ICE funding allocations that she says were paid for at the expense of SNAP and Medicaid and urged rescinding such funding to protect social-safety-net programs for children and working families. She has also pledged to sign a discharge petition for the "Hands Off Medicaid and SNAP Act" to defend Medicaid and SNAP from executive actions that would undermine benefits and access.
